    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_57519784" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/57519784" />
    <a title="Jessika" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1166992-jessika"><img alt="Jessika" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608048818p2/1166992.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/57519784?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessika" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessika" href="/user/show/1166992-jessika">Jessika</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805054453" href="/book/show/2893225-the-black-flower">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=wishlist">wishlist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166992-jessika?shelf=library">library</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer57519784" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13558989085522434903">Don&apos;t let the subtitle scare you off if you&apos;re not very interested in the Civil War. This book is so much more than a &quot;novel of the Civil War.&quot; It has appeal for everyone--if you&apos;re a Civil War nut (like myself), there&apos;s enough historical accuracy and apparent research to satisfy your thirst; if you&apos;re not really into history, there are enough human relationships and stories to keep you on the edge of your seat. Howard Bahr weaves this 48-hour story with such eloquence and insight that I wanted </span>
  <span id="freeText13558989085522434903" style="display:none">Don't let the subtitle scare you off if you're not very interested in the Civil War. This book is so much more than a "novel of the Civil War." It has appeal for everyone--if you're a Civil War nut (like myself), there's enough historical accuracy and apparent research to satisfy your thirst; if you're not really into history, there are enough human relationships and stories to keep you on the edge of your seat. Howard Bahr weaves this 48-hour story with such eloquence and insight that I wanted to savor each and every last page. He writes with amazing detail to create this beautiful prose that evoked so many different emotions out of me--fright, grief, hopefulness (and hopelessness), pain, anger--that once I had finished the novel, I felt like I had actually been there. This story is very real and hauntingly sad--I know I won't soon forget it. He creates scenes and characters that are incredibly memorable. Not to use cliche again, but I felt as if I were there and as if I actually knew these people. I <i>hated</i> Simon Rope, I rooted for Bushrod, I laughed at Jack Bishop, I felt for Anna, and I felt sorry for Nebo, to name a few. It takes an excellent author to make me feel so much towards a set of characters. I also particularly enjoyed the fact that Bahr did not write this novel in strict chronological, single-character-point-of-view, but rather bounced all around, incorporating different scenes and different points-of-view. To me, it was very reminiscent of what a battle and its aftermath would be like--scattered and chaotic. What makes it even better is that Bahr embraces this chaos while using it to form smooth transitions for his reader. The character development was amazing, as well. Through his characters, he deeply examines the psychological, emotional, and physical toll that battle takes on soldiers and civilians. Overall, this is now ranked among my favorites, and I have to say that this is everything that a Civil War/historical fiction should be and more. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13558989085522434903" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

