    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1008728885" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1008728885" />
    <a title="Linda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5841287-linda"><img alt="Linda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544123330p2/5841287.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1008728885?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda" href="/user/show/5841287-linda">Linda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1008728885" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14743131611998134341">About 20 pages into this story I began to chuckle. That chuckle gave way to rip roaring out loud laughing. Gomer Pyle meets Barney Fife in the trenches of the American Civil War. Beneath the mirth the Black Flower grows, overtaking the merriment. In it&apos;s place, despair. <br/><br/>Confederate and Union soldiers have put out the white flag for a cease-fire. Shoulder to shoulder they bury the &quot;Departed&quot;. “We need to bury these boys so we can commence to shooting some more “ says the Confederate officer. The </span>
  <span id="freeText14743131611998134341" style="display:none">About 20 pages into this story I began to chuckle. That chuckle gave way to rip roaring out loud laughing. Gomer Pyle meets Barney Fife in the trenches of the American Civil War. Beneath the mirth the Black Flower grows, overtaking the merriment. In it's place, despair. <br /><br />Confederate and Union soldiers have put out the white flag for a cease-fire. Shoulder to shoulder they bury the "Departed". “We need to bury these boys so we can commence to shooting some more “ says the Confederate officer. The blue and the gray uniform jackets of opposition cast aside, they’re just men out in a field sharing a task of burying the Departed. “Ain’t it curious what we’ve all come to?” says one to another. I imagine that question has been asked on every battlefield of every war that man has ever fought since the first conflict of our human species. <br /><br />Is this a good book? Yes, it’s a good little book but a very sad one indeed. The story centers around 3 young friends, Bushrod Carter, Virgil C. Johnson and Jack Bishop. It's about how they have each other's back, how they cope and how they spend their final days. This is the true blood and guts of a people turned on themselves. Two stars not because it isn't written well or true to the times, two stars because it's really not what I like to spend my time reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14743131611998134341" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


