    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_462169443" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/462169443" />
    <a title="Thing Two" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3722823-thing-two"><img alt="Thing Two" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500721584p2/3722823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/462169443?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thing Two" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thing Two" href="/user/show/3722823-thing-two">Thing Two</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Thing Two by: </span>
      Southern Lit Book Club
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3722823-thing-two?shelf=state-mississippi">state-mississippi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3722823-thing-two?shelf=history-civil-war">history-civil-war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer462169443" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6393052573108739088">Howard Bahr has written a non-traditional Civil War novel, one that doesn&apos;t give you dates, and places, and battle cries. There are plenty of authors who have done this already. What Bahr imagines here is what it was like to be in the protagonist&apos;s head, one Bushrod Carter, a private for the Confederate Army fighting in the Battle of Franklin, Tennessee. Bahr has us grieve the death of his companions, question the motives of his leaders, and try to stay focused and alive-while-dying by concentra</span>
  <span id="freeText6393052573108739088" style="display:none">Howard Bahr has written a non-traditional Civil War novel, one that doesn't give you dates, and places, and battle cries. There are plenty of authors who have done this already. What Bahr imagines here is what it was like to be in the protagonist's head, one Bushrod Carter, a private for the Confederate Army fighting in the Battle of Franklin, Tennessee. Bahr has us grieve the death of his companions, question the motives of his leaders, and try to stay focused and alive-while-dying by concentrating on the movement of wasps in the house turned hospital caught in the middle of this 1864 battle. I've never thought about wasps. I've never thought about waking up to a battle outside of my bedroom window. Bahr made me think.<br /><br />Yes, the story is depressing; it doesn't attempt to glorify the war, it doesn't attempt to bombard the reader with facts - although, that is not to say the book isn't extremely well researched! - it doesn't even make an overt political statement, other than to say that war is agony, and Bahr does this brilliantly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6393052573108739088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

